{
  "doc_id": "31389",
  "text": "In [CITATION_1] , Thorne, Kishino, and Felsenstein presented a method for pair-wise alignment of DNA sequences using a maximum likelihood (ML) approach. They developed an explicit statistical model of evolution that uses statistical insertions, deletions, and substitutions of nucleotides as basic operations for comparing two DNA sequences. An evolutionary model, that is given as input, determines at which rate these three evolutionary events occur. These rates are then used to design a dynamic programming (DP) algorithm that computes the ML pair-wise alignment between two DNA sequences.",
